{"declarations":[{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./Mathlib/Tactic/Cases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.cases'\"><span class=\"name\">Mathlib</span>.<span class=\"name\">Tactic</span>.<span class=\"name\">cases'</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Lean.ParserDescr\">Lean.ParserDescr</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"`cases' x`, where the variable `x` has inductive type `t`, splits the main goal,\nproducing one goal for each constructor of `t`, in which `x` is replaced by that constructor\napplied to newly introduced variables. This is a backwards-compatible variant of the\n`cases` tactic in Lean 4 core.\n\nPrefer `cases`, `rcases`, or `obtain` when possible, because these tactics promote\nstructured proofs.\n\n* `cases' x with n1 n2 ...` names the arguments to the constructors. This is the main difference\n  with `cases` in core Lean.\n* `cases' e`, where `e` is an expression instead of a variable, generalizes `e` in the goal,\n  and then performs induction on the resulting variable.\n* `cases' h : e`, where `e` is an expression instead of a variable, generalizes `e` in the goal,\n  and then splits by cases on the resulting variable, adding to each goal the hypothesis\n  `h : e = _` where `_` is the constructor instance.\n* `cases' x using r` uses `r` as the case matching rule. Here `r` should be a term whose result type\n  is of the form `C t1 t2 ...`, where `C` is a bound variable and `t1`, `t2`, ... (if present) are\n  bound variables.\n\nExample:\n```\nexample (h : p ∨ q) : q ∨ p := by\n  cases' h with hp hq\n  · exact Or.inr hp\n  · exact Or.inl hq\n\n-- Though the following equivalent spellings should be preferred\nexample (h : p ∨ q) : q ∨ p := by\n  cases h with\n  | inl hp => exact Or.inr hp\n  | inr hq => exact Or.inl hq\n\nexample (h : p ∨ q) : q ∨ p := by\n  rcases h with hp | hq\n  · exact Or.inr hp\n  · exact Or.inl hq\n```\n","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/Cases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.cases'","kind":"def","line":151,"name":"Mathlib.Tactic.cases'","sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/0f1dd7505c3d08b5feb82300ccc73179a457bf51/Mathlib/Tactic/Cases.lean#L151-L207"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./Mathlib/Tactic/Cases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.induction'\"><span class=\"name\">Mathlib</span>.<span class=\"name\">Tactic</span>.<span class=\"name\">induction'</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Lean.ParserDescr\">Lean.ParserDescr</a></div></div>","info":{"doc":"`induction' x` applies induction on the variable `x` of the inductive type `t` to the main goal,\nproducing one goal for each constructor of `t`, in which `x` is replaced by that constructor\napplied to newly introduced variables. `induction'` adds an inductive hypothesis for\neach recursive argument to the constructor. This is a backwards-compatible variant of the\n`induction` tactic in Lean 4 core.\n\nPrefer `induction` when possible, because it promotes structured proofs.\n\n* `induction' x with n1 n2 ...` names the introduced hypotheses: arguments to constructors and\n  inductive hypotheses. This is the main difference with `induction` in core Lean.\n* `induction' e`, where `e` is an expression instead of a variable, generalizes `e` in the goal,\n  and then performs induction on the resulting variable.\n* `induction' h : e`, where `e` is an expression instead of a variable, generalizes `e` in the goal,\n  and then performs induction on the resulting variable, adding to each goal the hypothesis\n  `h : e = _` where `_` is the constructor instance.\n* `induction' x using r` uses `r` as the principle of induction. Here `r` should be a term whose\n  result type is of the form `C t1 t2 ...`, where `C` is a bound variable and `t1`, `t2`, ... (if\n  present) are bound variables.\n* `induction' x generalizing z1 z2 ...` generalizes over the local variables `z1`, `z2`, ... in the\n  inductive hypothesis.\n\nExample:\n```\nopen Nat\n\nexample (n : ℕ) : 0 < factorial n := by\n  induction' n with n ih\n  · rw [factorial_zero]\n    simp\n  · rw [factorial_succ]\n    apply mul_pos (succ_pos n) ih\n\n-- Though the following equivalent spellings should be preferred\nexample (n : ℕ) : 0 < factorial n := by\n  induction n\n  case zero =>\n    rw [factorial_zero]\n    simp\n  case succ n ih =>\n    rw [factorial_succ]\n    apply mul_pos (succ_pos n) ih\n```\n","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/Cases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.induction'","kind":"def","line":75,"name":"Mathlib.Tactic.induction'","sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/0f1dd7505c3d08b5feb82300ccc73179a457bf51/Mathlib/Tactic/Cases.lean#L75-L149"}},{"header":"<div class=\"decl_header\"><span class=\"decl_kind\">def</span>\n<span class=\"decl_name\"><a class=\"break_within\" href=\"./Mathlib/Tactic/Cases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.ElimApp.evalNames\"><span class=\"name\">Mathlib</span>.<span class=\"name\">Tactic</span>.<span class=\"name\">ElimApp</span>.<span class=\"name\">evalNames</span></a></span><span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">elimInfo</span> : <a href=\"./Lean/Meta/Tactic/ElimInfo.html#Lean.Meta.ElimInfo\">Lean.Meta.ElimInfo</a>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">alts</span> : <span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Array\">Array</a> <a href=\"./Lean/Elab/Tactic/Induction.html#Lean.Elab.Tactic.ElimApp.Alt\">Lean.Elab.Tactic.ElimApp.Alt</a></span>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">withArg</span> : <a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Lean.Syntax\">Lean.Syntax</a>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">numEqs</span> : <a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Nat\">ℕ</a> := <span class=\"fn\">0</span>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">generalized </span><span class=\"fn\">toClear</span> : <span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Array\">Array</a> <a href=\"./Lean/Expr.html#Lean.FVarId\">Lean.FVarId</a></span> := <a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#List.toArray\">#[</a><a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#List.toArray\">]</a>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"decl_args\">\n<span class=\"fn\">(<span class=\"fn\">toTag</span> : <span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Array\">Array</a> (<a href=\"./Init/Meta/Defs.html#Lean.Syntax.Ident\">Lean.Ident</a> <a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Prod\">×</a> <a href=\"./Lean/Expr.html#Lean.FVarId\">Lean.FVarId</a>)</span> := <a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#List.toArray\">#[</a><a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#List.toArray\">]</a>)</span></span>\n<span class=\"decl_args\"> :</span><div class=\"decl_type\"><span class=\"fn\"><a href=\"./Lean/Elab/Term/TermElabM.html#Lean.Elab.Term.TermElabM\">Lean.Elab.TermElabM</a> <span class=\"fn\">(<a href=\"./Init/Prelude.html#Array\">Array</a> <a href=\"./Lean/Expr.html#Lean.MVarId\">Lean.MVarId</a>)</span></span></div></div>","info":{"doc":"","docLink":"./Mathlib/Tactic/Cases.html#Mathlib.Tactic.ElimApp.evalNames","kind":"def","line":51,"name":"Mathlib.Tactic.ElimApp.evalNames","sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/0f1dd7505c3d08b5feb82300ccc73179a457bf51/Mathlib/Tactic/Cases.lean#L51-L73"}}],"imports":["Init","Lean.Elab.Tactic.Induction","Batteries.Data.List.Basic","Batteries.Lean.Expr","Lean.Elab.Tactic.Induction","Mathlib.Init"],"instances":[],"name":"Mathlib.Tactic.Cases"}